Newer models are promising but not sufficient. They do better with existing data, but are nowhere near AGI.

A more serious discussion can be found with Sutton and Lecunn, who are open about the algorithmic limitations.

Understandable hype from the antrophic CEO...but hype nonetheless.

Viewed OpenAI admits hallucinations are inevitable.

Language models generate text token by token. Each word is a probabilistic guess, not a fact.

But most benchmarks score on correctness instead of confidence. That means models are encouraged to give any possible correct answer to all questions.

Benchmark Question: When is my birthday?
Model: <There are 365 days in a year>
<If I guess something, I have a 1/365 chance of getting it right>
<If I guess nothing, I get a score if ZERO.>
Your birthday is on 1st January.

It's like an entrance exam with no negative score for wrong answers. Any answer is better than no answer.

This encourages hallucinations. The problem is baked into evaluation datasets.

OpenAI is calling for an industry-wide change in benchmarks. 

Future models should be rewarded for admitting uncertainty, instead of random guessing.

Let's see if Google and DeepSeek tag along.

#AI #Hallucinations

When you paste a link into ChatGPT's textbox, it starts loading the page in the background.

This means time saved for page loading, vectorization, and KV-cache warmup. The resultant responses are instantaneous.

The concept isn't new. Instagram does something similar by asking users to add a description while their photos upload in the background. 

Because faster responses lead to better user engagement.
